===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{Han compound|ls=psc|卜|鬼|c1=s|c2=p}}. In the bronze inscriptions, {{och-l|*心}} and {{och-l|*攴}} were sometimes added. During the Warring States period, the {{och-l|*卜}} corrupted into {{och-l|*止}}<ref>{{R:yue:Hanzi}}</ref>.

Hsiao-ting Li: In oracle bone script form, this character depicts a ghost {{och-l|*鬼}} standing and holding a stick.

''{{w|Shuowen}}'' mistakes the small seal glyph as a ghost head ({{och-l|*甶}}) with part of a tiger, including its claw.

===Etymology===
Exoactive derivative of {{och-l|威|to overawe}}, lit. "to be intimidated" ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}).

